Thursday comes before Friday.","Information sheet: Scientific explanations of happiness

You are invited to take part in a study named “Scientific explanations of happiness”. This research is being conducted by Shilaan Alzahawi (shilaan@stanford.edu) and Benoît Monin (monin@stanford.edu).

column2: Purpose: This study will gather a participant’s thoughts on the results of a hypothetical scientific study on happiness.

What you will have to do: The study consists of reading about a scientific study and its results, followed by a series of questions relating to the research, including some questions about judgments and beliefs regarding the findings. Your participation will take about 8-12 minutes, which includes reading this consent information sheet.

Benefits: You will be paid $2 for your participation. We cannot and do not guarantee that you will receive any benefits from this study. This research may make you more aware of how knowledge is discovered in psychology and help the investigator better understand how people form social judgments. If you decide to participate, you will fill in a questionnaire.
Risk: There are no known risks associated with these studies.
What if I do not want to take part? Participation in this study is voluntary and you can choose not to take part or to stop your involvement in this study at given any time.

What happens at the end of the study? At the end of the study the information will be used for educational purposes, and analyses. The information will be completely confidential. No participant’s name will appear in any of the results. The data will be provided to other researchers but without identifying information. Information that is stored on a work computer will be stored (by the research team) on a computer that is password protected.

What if I have more questions or do not understand something? If you have any questions about the study you may contact either of the researchers. It is important that you feel that all your questions have been asked.

column1: Independent Contact:  If you are not satisfied with how this study is being conducted, or if you have any concerns, complaints, or general questions about the research or your rights as a participant, please contact the Stanford Institutional Review Board (IRB) to speak to someone independent of the research team at 650-723-2480 or toll free at 1-866-680-2906, or email at irbnonmed@stanford.edu.  You can also write to the Stanford IRB, Stanford University, 1705 El Camino Real, Palo Alto, CA 94306
